To test your ESP32, you can start with a simple code snippet that will help you check basic functionalities like Wi-Fi connection and serial output. Here’s a sample code that connects to a Wi-Fi network and prints the IP address:

```cpp
#include <WiFi.h>

const char* ssid = "YOUR_SSID";  // Replace with your network SSID
const char* password = "YOUR_PASSWORD";  // Replace with your network password

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  delay(1000);

  // Connect to Wi-Fi
  WiFi.begin(ssid, password);
  Serial.print("Connecting to WiFi");

  while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) {
    delay(500);
    Serial.print(".");
  }

  Serial.println();
  Serial.println("Connected to WiFi!");
  Serial.print("IP Address: ");
  Serial.println(WiFi.localIP());
}

void loop() {
  // You can add more tests here
}
```

Replace `YOUR_SSID` and `YOUR_PASSWORD` with your actual Wi-Fi credentials. Upload this code to your ESP32, and open the Serial Monitor to see the output. Would you like me to explain any part of the code further?
